---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="Electrical & Solar">
  <span class="page-tag">Power</span>
  <h1>Electrical &amp; Solar</h1>
  <p class="lead">50A service, ground-mounted solar, battery storage in outbuilding.</p>

  <h2>House Electrical</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Service:</strong> 50A inlet plug with internal breaker panel. Source-agnostic — grid, solar microgrid, or RV hookup.</li>
    <li><strong>Key circuits:</strong> Induction cooktop (20A 120V), minisplit (20A 240V), washer/dryer (20–30A 240V), bathroom water heater (20A 120V), kitchen water heater (120V shared), dishdrawer (20A 120V), air fryer oven (20A 120V), range hood (shared), fridge (120V shared), general outlets + lighting.</li>
    <li><strong>Smart load management panel recommended</strong> — prevents tripping by pausing water heaters or W/D when cooktop is running full blast.</li>
    <li><strong>Daily consumption:</strong> ~10–15 kWh/day depending on season. Peak: 5–7 kW realistic.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Solar — Shared Components</h2>
  <p>Same for all battery options:</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Est. Cost</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Panels: 8–10 &times; 400W (~3.5–4 kW) ground-mounted</td><td>$2,000–2,800</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ground mount racking</td><td>$800–1,200</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Inverter: <strong>Sol-Ark 5K</strong> — <a href="https://www.sol-ark.com/residential/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sol-Ark</a></td><td>$1,800–2,500</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Wiring, combiner box, breakers, conduit</td><td>$500–800</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Outbuilding (simple shed for electrical)</td><td>$500–1,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Shared subtotal</strong></td><td><strong>$5,600–8,300</strong></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Battery Option A: Salvaged EV Batteries</h2>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Est. Cost</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Salvaged Nissan Leaf or Chevy Bolt modules (~20–25 kWh) + BMS + enclosure</td><td>$1,400–3,300</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Total system (Option A)</strong></td><td><strong>$7,000–11,600</strong></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p><strong>Pros:</strong> cheapest, environmentally great (reuse), generous capacity. <strong>Cons:</strong> high DIY complexity, NMC chemistry (needs ventilation), no warranty, unknown cycle life.</p>

  <h2>Battery Option B: Renogy LFP (Full Size)</h2>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Est. Cost</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>8&times; <a href="https://www.renogy.com/products/core-12v-200ah-lithium-iron-phosphate-battery-w-bluetooth" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Renogy Core 12V 200Ah</a> (4S2P = 48V, 20.48 kWh)</td><td>$5,600–6,400</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Total system (Option B)</strong></td><td><strong>$11,200–14,700</strong></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p><strong>Pros:</strong> plug-and-play, LFP chemistry (safer, 5,000 cycles / ~14 years), 5-year warranty, bluetooth monitoring, self-heating option. <strong>Cons:</strong> 2–3&times; battery cost vs EV salvage.</p>

  <h2>Battery Option B-lite: Starter + Expand Later</h2>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Component</th><th>Est. Cost</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>4&times; Renogy Core 12V 200Ah (4S = 48V, 10.24 kWh) + small backup generator</td><td>$3,200–4,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Total system (Option B-lite)</strong></td><td><strong>$8,800–12,300</strong></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="decision">
    <p><strong>Sweet spot option:</strong> Start with 10 kWh, use generator or grid for gaps, add another 4-battery string later as prices drop. Sol-Ark and Renogy systems designed for this expansion.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Inverter: Sol-Ark vs Victron</h2>

  <h3>Sol-Ark 5K (preferred for now)</h3>
  <p>All-in-one (inverter + charge controller + transfer switch), simple install, US-certified, built-in 120/240V split-phase. ~$1,800–2,500. Best for a single tiny house. — <a href="https://www.sol-ark.com/residential/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sol-Ark</a></p>

  <h3>Victron MultiPlus-II</h3>
  <p>Modular (separate inverter + MPPT + monitoring), legendary build quality, transformer-based (better surge handling), excellent for future microgrid scaling. More complex install, more expensive (~$2,500–4,000 for equivalent system). Better if building shared microgrid from day one. — <a href="https://www.victronenergy.com/inverters-chargers/multiplus-ii" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Victron MultiPlus-II</a></p>

  <div class="page-nav">
    <a href={`${base}rainwater/`}>&larr; Rainwater</a>
    <a href={`${base}open-questions/`} class="next">Open Questions &rarr;</a>
  </div>
</Layout>
